WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.410 --> 00:00:03.549
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: So,

00:00:03.549 --> 00:00:06.647
today we are going to do
something different from what's

00:00:06.647 --> 00:00:09.181
happened so far,
in that we are going to study

00:00:09.181 --> 00:00:11.490
the dynamics of more than one
body.

00:00:11.490 --> 00:00:15.619
Well, you might say "Look,
we already did this last week,

00:00:15.619 --> 00:00:18.200
when I studied the Solar
System,"

00:00:18.200 --> 00:00:21.074
where there are planets moving
around the Sun so that makes at

00:00:21.074 --> 00:00:23.260
least two bodies,
the Sun and the planet.

00:00:23.260 --> 00:00:25.239
But actually,
the Sun was not doing anything

00:00:25.239 --> 00:00:28.364
interesting in our analysis.
The Sun just stood there as a

00:00:28.364 --> 00:00:30.470
source of the gravitational
force.

00:00:30.470 --> 00:00:34.204
It's the planet that did all
the orbiting and that was the

00:00:34.204 --> 00:00:37.480
problem in two dimensions,
but of only one body.

00:00:37.480 --> 00:00:43.331
So now, we are going to enlarge
our domain to more than one body

00:00:43.331 --> 00:00:47.678
obeying Newton's laws.
So, let me start with the

00:00:47.678 --> 00:00:50.730
simplest possible case:
two bodies.

00:00:50.730 --> 00:00:54.198
And I will again start with the
simplest case of their moving in

00:00:54.198 --> 00:00:57.050
one dimension;
then, we'll put in more.

00:01:03.990 --> 00:01:08.878
So, here is the one-dimensional
world in which these bodies are

00:01:08.878 --> 00:01:12.146
going to move,
and this is my origin,

00:01:12.146 --> 00:01:15.887
x = 0,
and I'm going to imagine one

00:01:15.887 --> 00:01:19.583
point mass m_1,
located at

00:01:19.583 --> 00:01:21.548
x_1,
another point mass

00:01:21.548 --> 00:01:23.110
m_2,
located at

00:01:23.110 --> 00:01:24.420
x_2.

00:01:31.650 --> 00:01:35.486
Now, we know everything there
is to know about these masses

00:01:35.486 --> 00:01:39.190
from the laws of Newton which
I'm going to write down.

00:01:39.190 --> 00:01:43.154
The first mass obeys this
equation, m_1

00:01:43.154 --> 00:01:47.489
d^(2)x_1/ dt^(2).
That's ma, right?

00:01:47.489 --> 00:01:51.220
But I'm going to write this in
a notation that's more succinct.

00:01:51.220 --> 00:01:53.879
I'm tired of writing the second
derivative in this fashion.

00:01:53.879 --> 00:01:56.957
I'm going to write it as
follows, m_1x

00:01:56.957 --> 00:01:59.420
_1,
with two dots on it;

00:01:59.420 --> 00:02:02.033
the two dots telling you it's
two derivatives,

00:02:02.033 --> 00:02:05.110
because one dot is one
derivative, three dots is three

00:02:05.110 --> 00:02:07.530
derivatives.
Of course, at some point this

00:02:07.530 --> 00:02:10.305
notation becomes unwieldy,
but you never deal with more

00:02:10.305 --> 00:02:12.310
than two derivatives,
so this works.

00:02:12.310 --> 00:02:16.102
This is ma,
so don't forget the dots,

00:02:16.102 --> 00:02:17.990
okay?
This is not some foreign

00:02:17.990 --> 00:02:20.289
alphabet.
Every dot is a derivative.

00:02:20.289 --> 00:02:23.650
You should remember that when I
do subsequent manipulation.

00:02:23.650 --> 00:02:26.231
That's ma,
and that's equal to force on

00:02:26.231 --> 00:02:28.010
body 1, F_1.

00:02:31.699 --> 00:02:35.307
Now, look at the body one and
ask, "What are the forces acting

00:02:35.307 --> 00:02:37.387
on it?"
Well, it could be the whole

00:02:37.387 --> 00:02:40.033
universe.
But we're going to divide that

00:02:40.033 --> 00:02:43.267
into two parts.
The first part is going to be

00:02:43.267 --> 00:02:47.815
the force on body 1 due to body
2, which I'm going to denote by

00:02:47.815 --> 00:02:50.699
F_12;
that's our notation.

00:02:50.699 --> 00:02:53.190
You and I agree that it's the
force on 1 due to 2.

00:02:53.190 --> 00:02:59.030
Then, there's the force on 1
due to the external world;

00:02:59.030 --> 00:03:01.778
e stands for external.
That means everything outside

00:03:01.778 --> 00:03:03.620
these two.
So, the universe has many

00:03:03.620 --> 00:03:05.362
bodies;
I have just picked these two

00:03:05.362 --> 00:03:06.838
guys.
They're 1 and 2,

00:03:06.838 --> 00:03:10.106
and the force on 1 is--some of
it's due to 2,

00:03:10.106 --> 00:03:13.300
and some of it's due to
everything else.

00:03:16.560 --> 00:03:20.760
Similarly, I have another
equation, m_2x

00:03:20.760 --> 00:03:25.768
_2 double dot is
the force on 2 due to 1 plus the

00:03:25.768 --> 00:03:29.000
force on 2 due to the outside
world.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:30.280
What do you mean by "outside
world"?

00:03:30.280 --> 00:03:32.464
Maybe these two guys are next
to some planet,

00:03:32.464 --> 00:03:34.500
and the planet's way over to
the right,

00:03:34.500 --> 00:03:37.121
it's pulling all of them
towards the planet with some

00:03:37.121 --> 00:03:39.906
gravitational force.
So, everything else is called

00:03:39.906 --> 00:03:42.377
"external."
And I have 1 and 2,

00:03:42.377 --> 00:03:46.120
for example,
are connected by a spring.

00:03:46.120 --> 00:03:47.849
The spring is not that
important.

00:03:47.849 --> 00:03:50.441
It's a way of transmitting
force from one body to the

00:03:50.441 --> 00:03:52.622
other.
If you compress the spring and

00:03:52.622 --> 00:03:56.424
let it go, these two masses will
vibrate back and forth under the

00:03:56.424 --> 00:03:58.860
influence of the other person's
force.

00:03:58.860 --> 00:04:00.412
That's an example of
F_12 and

00:04:00.412 --> 00:04:01.856
F_21.
For example,

00:04:01.856 --> 00:04:04.065
if the spring is compressed at
this instant,

00:04:04.065 --> 00:04:06.797
it's trying to push them out;
that means, really,

00:04:06.797 --> 00:04:10.058
1 is trying to push 2 out,
whereas that way 2 is trying to

00:04:10.058 --> 00:04:11.889
push 1 to the left,
this way.

00:04:11.889 --> 00:04:14.120
That's an example of
F_12 and

00:04:14.120 --> 00:04:17.149
F_21.
The external force could be due

00:04:17.149 --> 00:04:19.819
to something extraneous to these
two bodies.

00:04:19.819 --> 00:04:24.329
So, one example is at the
surface of the Earth.

00:04:24.329 --> 00:04:27.689
I take these two masses
connected by a spring.

00:04:27.689 --> 00:04:30.350
Here is mass 1 and here's mass
2.

00:04:30.350 --> 00:04:33.337
I squash the spring.
If there is no gravity,

00:04:33.337 --> 00:04:37.573
they will just go vibrating up
and down but let them fall into

00:04:37.573 --> 00:04:40.668
the field of gravity,
so they're also experiencing

00:04:40.668 --> 00:04:43.830
the mg due to gravity.
So, they will both fall down

00:04:43.830 --> 00:04:46.449
and also oscillate a little with
each other.

00:04:46.449 --> 00:04:48.440
They're all described by this
equation.

00:04:48.440 --> 00:04:51.720
This will be the spring force
transmitted from 1 to 2.

00:04:51.720 --> 00:04:54.123
This will be the force of
gravity, or it could be an

00:04:54.123 --> 00:04:56.810
electric force or any other
force due to anything else;

00:04:56.810 --> 00:04:59.640
we are not interested.
Now, here is the interesting

00:04:59.640 --> 00:05:01.610
manipulation we're going to
perform.

00:05:01.610 --> 00:05:05.025
We are going to add the two
things on the left-hand side and

00:05:05.025 --> 00:05:08.209
equate them to whatever I get on
the right-hand side.

00:05:08.209 --> 00:05:14.035
Then, m_1x
_1 double dot plus

00:05:14.035 --> 00:05:19.120
m_2x
_2 double dot,

00:05:19.120 --> 00:05:22.721
and that's going to be--I'm
going to write it in a

00:05:22.721 --> 00:05:25.220
particular way,
F_1e +

00:05:25.220 --> 00:05:29.410
F_2e + F_12
+ F_21.

00:05:33.519 --> 00:05:36.490
I think you have some idea of
where I'm headed now.

00:05:36.490 --> 00:05:39.830
So, what's the next thing we
could say?

00:05:39.830 --> 00:05:41.242
Yes?
Student:

00:05:41.242 --> 00:05:43.009
F_12 +
F_21 = 0.

00:05:43.009 --> 00:05:44.082
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: Yes,

00:05:44.082 --> 00:05:45.209
because that's the Third Law of
Newton.

00:05:45.209 --> 00:05:47.970
Whatever the underlying force,
gravity, spring,

00:05:47.970 --> 00:05:51.703
anything, force on 1 due to 2,
and force on 2 due to 1 will

00:05:51.703 --> 00:05:55.264
cancel, and everything I get
today, the whole lecture is

00:05:55.264 --> 00:05:57.790
mainly about this one simple
result,

00:05:57.790 --> 00:06:01.769
this cancellation.
Then, this whole thing,

00:06:01.769 --> 00:06:04.763
I'm going to write as
F_e,

00:06:04.763 --> 00:06:09.040
meaning the total external
force on this two-body system.

00:06:13.370 --> 00:06:15.220
So, I have this peculiar
equation.

00:06:15.220 --> 00:06:18.666
I'm going to rewrite it in a
way that brings it to the form

00:06:18.666 --> 00:06:22.998
in which it's most useful.
I'm going to introduce a new

00:06:22.998 --> 00:06:26.007
guy, capital X.
As you know,

00:06:26.007 --> 00:06:30.160
that's called a center of mass
coordinate, and it's defined as

00:06:30.160 --> 00:06:34.313
m_1x_1 +
m_2x_2

00:06:34.313 --> 00:06:37.712
divided by capital M.
Capital M is just the

00:06:37.712 --> 00:06:39.770
total mass, m_1 +
m_2.

00:06:44.160 --> 00:06:46.750
If I do that,
this is a definition.

00:06:46.750 --> 00:06:50.860
Then, we can write this
equation as follows.

00:06:50.860 --> 00:06:56.560
I will write it and then we can
take our time seeing that it is

00:06:56.560 --> 00:06:58.476
correct.
So, this is really the big

00:06:58.476 --> 00:06:58.860
equation.

00:07:03.040 --> 00:07:06.020
Why don't you guys try to fill
in the blanks in your head?

00:07:06.020 --> 00:07:09.529
This is really correct.
On the left-hand side,

00:07:09.529 --> 00:07:14.721
I have M times X
double dot, so I have really

00:07:14.721 --> 00:07:19.197
m_1 +
m_2 times X

00:07:19.197 --> 00:07:22.206
double dot.
If you take the double dot of

00:07:22.206 --> 00:07:25.686
this guy, it's m_1x
_1 double dot plus

00:07:25.686 --> 00:07:28.350
m_2x
_2 double dot,

00:07:28.350 --> 00:07:31.829
divided by m_1 +
m_2.

00:07:31.829 --> 00:07:34.370
So, the left-hand side is
indeed this;

00:07:34.370 --> 00:07:37.588
that's all I want you to check.
So, take this expression,

00:07:37.588 --> 00:07:40.639
divide by the total mass and
multiply by the total mass.

00:07:40.639 --> 00:07:42.723
Well, the multiplying by the
total mass is here,

00:07:42.723 --> 00:07:45.161
and when you divide by the
total mass you get the second

00:07:45.161 --> 00:07:47.290
derivative of the center of mass
coordinate.

00:07:53.370 --> 00:07:58.065
So what have I done?
I have introduced a fictitious

00:07:58.065 --> 00:08:02.266
entity, the center of mass.
The center of mass is a

00:08:02.266 --> 00:08:04.921
location X,
some kind of a weighted average

00:08:04.921 --> 00:08:07.740
of x_1 and
x_2.

00:08:07.740 --> 00:08:09.420
By weighted,
I mean if m_1

00:08:09.420 --> 00:08:10.899
and m_2 are
equal,

00:08:10.899 --> 00:08:13.679
then capital M will be
two times that mass and you'll

00:08:13.679 --> 00:08:16.269
just get x_1 +
x_2 over 2.

00:08:16.269 --> 00:08:18.339
The center of mass will sit
right in between.

00:08:18.339 --> 00:08:20.404
But if m_1 is
heavier, it'll be tilted towards

00:08:20.404 --> 00:08:22.017
m_1;
if m_2 is

00:08:22.017 --> 00:08:23.810
heavier, it'll be tilted towards
m_2.

00:08:23.810 --> 00:08:26.959
It's a weighted sum that gives
a certain coordinate.

00:08:26.959 --> 00:08:30.490
There is nothing present at
that location.

00:08:30.490 --> 00:08:33.736
There's nobody there.
All the stuff is either here or

00:08:33.736 --> 00:08:35.515
there.
The center of mass is the

00:08:35.515 --> 00:08:37.470
location of a mathematical
entity.

00:08:37.470 --> 00:08:39.820
It's not a physical entity.
If you go there and say,

00:08:39.820 --> 00:08:42.064
"What's at the center of mass?"
you typically won't find

00:08:42.064 --> 00:08:47.840
anything.
And it behaves like a body.

00:08:47.840 --> 00:08:50.644
After all, if you just said,
"I've learned Newton's laws,"

00:08:50.644 --> 00:08:52.759
and I walk into this room and I
say this,

00:08:52.759 --> 00:08:54.836
you will say "Well,
this guy's talking about a body

00:08:54.836 --> 00:08:57.805
of mass, capital M,
undergoing some acceleration

00:08:57.805 --> 00:09:01.476
due to the force."
So, the center of mass is the

00:09:01.476 --> 00:09:06.033
body whose mass seems to be the
total mass of these two

00:09:06.033 --> 00:09:08.603
particles,
whose acceleration is

00:09:08.603 --> 00:09:11.269
controlled by the same as
Newton's law,

00:09:11.269 --> 00:09:14.707
but the right-hand side
contains only the external

00:09:14.707 --> 00:09:17.000
forces;
this is the key.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:20.455
All the internal forces have
canceled out,

00:09:20.455 --> 00:09:23.909
and what remains is the
external force.

00:09:23.909 --> 00:09:26.504
Now it turns,
if you've got three bodies,

00:09:26.504 --> 00:09:28.840
you can do a similar
manipulation.

00:09:28.840 --> 00:09:30.381
And again, you'll have
F_12 and

00:09:30.381 --> 00:09:32.350
F_23 and
F_32 and so on.

00:09:32.350 --> 00:09:37.480
They will cancel and what will
remain will be a similar thing,

00:09:37.480 --> 00:09:40.759
but this is the total external
force.

00:09:40.759 --> 00:09:44.303
So, if I can say this in words,
what we have learned is that

00:09:44.303 --> 00:09:48.027
the advantage of introducing a
quantity called "center of mass"

00:09:48.027 --> 00:09:50.909
is that it responds only to the
total force;

00:09:50.909 --> 00:09:53.640
it doesn't care about internal
forces.

00:09:53.640 --> 00:09:59.710
So, I'll give an example.
Here is some airplane, right?

00:09:59.710 --> 00:10:02.692
It's in flight,
and a couple of guys are having

00:10:02.692 --> 00:10:05.350
a fight, punching each other and
so on.

00:10:05.350 --> 00:10:08.107
The rest of the passengers say
"enough is enough" and they

00:10:08.107 --> 00:10:10.341
throw them out.
So, they're just floating

00:10:10.341 --> 00:10:13.616
around, affecting each other's
dynamics, and of course this

00:10:13.616 --> 00:10:16.269
person will feel a force due to
that person,

00:10:16.269 --> 00:10:18.631
that person will feel a force
due to this person,

00:10:18.631 --> 00:10:21.682
but what I'm telling you is the
center of mass is going to drop

00:10:21.682 --> 00:10:24.386
like a rock.
It's going to accelerate with

00:10:24.386 --> 00:10:27.193
the force mgh;
it's going to accelerate with

00:10:27.193 --> 00:10:29.007
g.
So, at one point this person

00:10:29.007 --> 00:10:31.800
may be having the upper hand and
may be here, and the other

00:10:31.800 --> 00:10:34.599
person may be down here,
but follow the center of mass

00:10:34.599 --> 00:10:37.029
and you'll find it simply falls
under gravity.

00:10:37.029 --> 00:10:40.323
So, the mutual forces do not
affect the dynamics of the

00:10:40.323 --> 00:10:42.618
center of mass.
Or, for example,

00:10:42.618 --> 00:10:46.785
suppose at some point,
this person blows the other one

00:10:46.785 --> 00:10:49.187
up into,
say, it's a samurai bat,

00:10:49.187 --> 00:10:51.815
make it simple,
cuts him up in two pieces,

00:10:51.815 --> 00:10:55.596
so now we've got three bodies
now: the first protagonist and

00:10:55.596 --> 00:10:58.976
the other two now,
unfortunately somewhat

00:10:58.976 --> 00:11:01.810
decimated.
Now, you can take these three

00:11:01.810 --> 00:11:04.080
bodies, find their center of
mass;

00:11:04.080 --> 00:11:07.580
it'll be the same thing;
it'll just keep falling down.

00:11:07.580 --> 00:11:10.164
So, even though the system is
becoming more and more

00:11:10.164 --> 00:11:13.153
complicated, you cannot change
the dynamics of the center of

00:11:13.153 --> 00:11:15.131
mass.
It responds only to the

00:11:15.131 --> 00:11:17.633
external force.
If this fight was taking place

00:11:17.633 --> 00:11:20.425
in outer space where there's no
gravity, then as this fight

00:11:20.425 --> 00:11:23.649
continues and people are flying
and parts are flying everywhere,

00:11:23.649 --> 00:11:25.813
the center of mass will just be
in one location,

00:11:25.813 --> 00:11:27.899
not doing anything.
Yes?

00:11:27.899 --> 00:11:30.211
Student: Couldn't the
internal forces change the

00:11:30.211 --> 00:11:32.101
center of mass's location?
Professor Ramamurti

00:11:32.101 --> 00:11:33.389
Shankar: No,
that's what I'm saying.

00:11:33.389 --> 00:11:35.412
The center of mass,
if it changes it can

00:11:35.412 --> 00:11:37.902
certainly-- No one says the
center of mass cannot

00:11:37.902 --> 00:11:40.073
accelerate.
It can accelerate due to

00:11:40.073 --> 00:11:42.933
external forces.
But if there were no external

00:11:42.933 --> 00:11:47.004
forces, then the center of mass
will behave like a particle with

00:11:47.004 --> 00:11:49.154
no force.
If it's not moving to begin

00:11:49.154 --> 00:11:51.797
with, it won't move later.
Or if it is moving to begin

00:11:51.797 --> 00:11:53.770
with, it'll maintain a constant
velocity.

00:11:53.770 --> 00:11:58.482
So, here's another example.
Now you can obviously

00:11:58.482 --> 00:12:00.539
generalize this to more than one
dimension.

00:12:00.539 --> 00:12:04.298
If you're living in two
dimensions, you will introduce

00:12:04.298 --> 00:12:08.341
an x coordinate and
introduce a y coordinate

00:12:08.341 --> 00:12:12.099
and then you will have the
center of mass as MR

00:12:12.099 --> 00:12:16.305
double dot equals F,
and R would be

00:12:16.305 --> 00:12:21.723
m_1r_1 +
m_2r_2

00:12:21.723 --> 00:12:26.019
divided by the total mass;
r_1 and

00:12:26.019 --> 00:12:29.744
r_2 are just
the location now in two

00:12:29.744 --> 00:12:32.689
dimensions of these two masses.
So, here is

00:12:32.689 --> 00:12:35.470
m_1 and here is
m_2 and the

00:12:35.470 --> 00:12:38.250
center of mass you can check
will be somewhere in between the

00:12:38.250 --> 00:12:42.060
line joining the two points,
but it'll now be a vector.

00:12:42.060 --> 00:12:47.519
So here's another example.
You take a complicated object;

00:12:47.519 --> 00:12:49.070
it's got masses and it's got
springs;

00:12:49.070 --> 00:12:51.279
it's connected with thread,
and chains and everything.

00:12:51.279 --> 00:12:53.070
You throw the whole mess into
the air.

00:12:53.070 --> 00:12:55.759
All the different parts of it
are jiggling and doing

00:12:55.759 --> 00:12:58.555
complicated movements,
but if you follow the center of

00:12:58.555 --> 00:13:00.141
mass,
in other words at every instant

00:13:00.141 --> 00:13:01.682
you take the
m_1r_1 +

00:13:01.682 --> 00:13:03.762
m_2r_2 +
m_3r_3

00:13:03.762 --> 00:13:06.091
and so on,
divided by the total mass,

00:13:06.091 --> 00:13:10.294
that coordinate will simply be
following the parabolic path of

00:13:10.294 --> 00:13:13.915
a body curving under gravity.
If at some point this

00:13:13.915 --> 00:13:16.880
complicated object fragments
into two chunks,

00:13:16.880 --> 00:13:19.980
one will land here and one will
land there.

00:13:19.980 --> 00:13:22.711
But at every instant,
if you follow the center of

00:13:22.711 --> 00:13:26.240
mass, it'll go as if nothing
happened and it will land here.

00:13:26.240 --> 00:13:30.176
The center of mass does not
care about internal forces,

00:13:30.176 --> 00:13:33.610
only about external forces.
That's the main point.

00:13:33.610 --> 00:13:36.374
And it was designed in such a
way that external [correction:

00:13:36.374 --> 00:13:38.810
should have said "internal"]
forces canceled in these

00:13:38.810 --> 00:13:41.425
dynamics.
So, everything I'm going to do

00:13:41.425 --> 00:13:45.235
today is to take that equation,
MX..= F or MR..=

00:13:45.235 --> 00:13:48.176
F, in vector form,
and deduce some of the

00:13:48.176 --> 00:13:50.556
consequences.
Now, first of all,

00:13:50.556 --> 00:13:53.953
you should realize that if
you've got several bodies,

00:13:53.953 --> 00:13:56.980
say three bodies,
then I will define the center

00:13:56.980 --> 00:14:00.660
of mass to be m_ix
_i divided by the

00:14:00.660 --> 00:14:03.504
sum of m_i.
This is a shorthand,

00:14:03.504 --> 00:14:06.315
I'm going to write it only
once, but you should know what

00:14:06.315 --> 00:14:09.428
the notation means.
If there is i from 1 to

00:14:09.428 --> 00:14:12.708
3, it really means
m_1x_1 +

00:14:12.708 --> 00:14:16.591
m_2x_2 +
m_3x_3

00:14:16.591 --> 00:14:19.536
divided by m_1 +
m_2 +

00:14:19.536 --> 00:14:22.985
m_3.
This summation is the notation

00:14:22.985 --> 00:14:26.653
mathematicians have introduced
where the index i will go

00:14:26.653 --> 00:14:29.688
over a range from 1 to 3.
Every term you let i

00:14:29.688 --> 00:14:32.140
take three different values and
you do the sum.

00:14:36.500 --> 00:14:39.923
An exercise I've given to you
guys to pursue at home is the

00:14:39.923 --> 00:14:41.990
following: if I got three
bodies,

00:14:41.990 --> 00:14:45.488
1,2 and 3, you've defined the
center of mass,

00:14:45.488 --> 00:14:48.350
you can either go to this
formula,

00:14:48.350 --> 00:14:51.013
do all the m_1x
_1's and add them

00:14:51.013 --> 00:14:53.000
up, or you also have the
following option.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:56.346
You can pick any two of them,
say the first two -- forget the

00:14:56.346 --> 00:14:59.244
third one -- take these two,
find their center of mass,

00:14:59.244 --> 00:15:00.986
let's call it
x_1 and

00:15:00.986 --> 00:15:03.058
x_2 and with
that total mass

00:15:03.058 --> 00:15:06.095
M_12,
which is just m_1

00:15:06.095 --> 00:15:08.744
+ m_2,
trade these two for a new

00:15:08.744 --> 00:15:11.040
fictitious object and put that
here,

00:15:11.040 --> 00:15:14.247
and forget these two.
But on that one point it

00:15:14.247 --> 00:15:18.154
deposits the mass of these two;
now, you take the center of

00:15:18.154 --> 00:15:20.833
mass of this object with the
third object,

00:15:20.833 --> 00:15:24.809
by the same weighting process,
m_3x_3 +

00:15:24.809 --> 00:15:27.568
M_12X&lt;
sub&gt;12 divided by the

00:15:27.568 --> 00:15:32.375
total mass;
you'll get the same answer as

00:15:32.375 --> 00:15:34.231
here.
What I'm telling you is,

00:15:34.231 --> 00:15:36.765
if you've got many bodies and
you want the center of mass of

00:15:36.765 --> 00:15:39.517
all of them,
you can take a subset of them,

00:15:39.517 --> 00:15:42.750
replace them by their center of
mass, namely,

00:15:42.750 --> 00:15:44.947
all their mass sitting at their
center of mass,

00:15:44.947 --> 00:15:47.909
replace the other half by their
mass sitting at their center of

00:15:47.909 --> 00:15:50.286
mass,
and finally find the center of

00:15:50.286 --> 00:15:53.789
mass of these two centers of
mass, properly weighted,

00:15:53.789 --> 00:15:55.580
and that'll give you this
result.

00:15:59.960 --> 00:16:03.899
Okay, so, before I exploit that
equation and find all the

00:16:03.899 --> 00:16:06.924
consequences,
we have to get used to finding

00:16:06.924 --> 00:16:09.950
center of mass for a variety of
things,

00:16:09.950 --> 00:16:13.325
as long as they give you ten
masses, or a countable number of

00:16:13.325 --> 00:16:15.800
masses, we've just got to plug
it in here;

00:16:15.800 --> 00:16:20.092
it's a very trivial exercise.
Things become more interesting

00:16:20.092 --> 00:16:24.434
if I give you not a set of
discrete masses but discrete

00:16:24.434 --> 00:16:27.449
locations,
namely, a countable set of

00:16:27.449 --> 00:16:30.480
masses, but I give you a rod
like this.

00:16:30.480 --> 00:16:34.824
This is a rod of mass M
and length L,

00:16:34.824 --> 00:16:38.559
and I say: "Where is the center
of mass?"

00:16:38.559 --> 00:16:41.181
So, we have to adapt the
definition that we have for this

00:16:41.181 --> 00:16:41.650
problem.

00:16:44.980 --> 00:16:48.529
So, what should I do?
Well, this is my origin of

00:16:48.529 --> 00:16:50.809
coordinates.
If I had a set of masses with

00:16:50.809 --> 00:16:54.259
definite locations I know how to
do it, but this is a continuum.

00:16:54.259 --> 00:16:58.999
The trick then is to say,
I take a distance x from

00:16:58.999 --> 00:17:02.553
the left hand,
and I cut myself a very thin

00:17:02.553 --> 00:17:05.600
sliver of taking this dx.

00:17:09.440 --> 00:17:13.939
That sliver has got a certain
mass, and I argue it's at a

00:17:13.939 --> 00:17:18.599
definite distance x from
the coordinate's origin.

00:17:18.599 --> 00:17:21.213
And if you're nitpicking you
will say, "What do you mean by

00:17:21.213 --> 00:17:23.566
definite distance?"
It's got a width dx,

00:17:23.566 --> 00:17:26.328
so one part of it is at
x, the other part is at

00:17:26.328 --> 00:17:29.349
x + dx so it doesn't have
a definite coordinate.

00:17:29.349 --> 00:17:33.385
But if dx is going to 0,
this argument will eventually

00:17:33.385 --> 00:17:35.535
be invalid.
So dx goes to 0,

00:17:35.535 --> 00:17:38.695
sliver has a definite location,
which is just the x

00:17:38.695 --> 00:17:42.434
coordinate of where I put it.
So, to find the center of mass,

00:17:42.434 --> 00:17:46.172
which consists of multiplying
every mass by its location and

00:17:46.172 --> 00:17:49.910
adding--Let me first find how
much mass is sitting here.

00:17:49.910 --> 00:17:54.200
Let me call it δm.
How much mass is sitting there?

00:17:54.200 --> 00:17:57.057
Well, I do the following.
I take the total mass and

00:17:57.057 --> 00:18:01.160
divide it by L;
that's the mass per unit length.

00:18:01.160 --> 00:18:07.467
And this fellow has a width
dx, so the mass of this

00:18:07.467 --> 00:18:11.339
little sliver is (M/L)
dx.

00:18:11.339 --> 00:18:17.425
Therefore, the center of mass
that I want is found by taking

00:18:17.425 --> 00:18:22.118
this sliver of that mass,
multiplying by its coordinate

00:18:22.118 --> 00:18:25.737
and summing over all the
slivers, which is what we do by

00:18:25.737 --> 00:18:28.971
the integral from 0 to L.
Then, I should divide by the

00:18:28.971 --> 00:18:30.170
total mass, which is just
M.

00:18:34.529 --> 00:18:37.470
You can see now if you do this
calculation.

00:18:37.470 --> 00:18:41.276
I get 1/L;
then, I get integral xdx

00:18:41.276 --> 00:18:44.180
from 0 to L,
and that's going to be

00:18:44.180 --> 00:18:48.398
L^(2) over 2.
So, if you do that you'll get

00:18:48.398 --> 00:18:51.203
L/2.
I'm not doing every step in the

00:18:51.203 --> 00:18:54.447
calculus because at this point
we should be able to do this

00:18:54.447 --> 00:18:58.330
without every detail.
So, the center of mass of this

00:18:58.330 --> 00:19:02.819
rod, to nobody's surprise,
is right in the midpoint,

00:19:02.819 --> 00:19:06.862
but it assumes that the rod is
uniform, whereas [if its]

00:19:06.862 --> 00:19:09.735
like a baseball bat,
thicker at one end and thinner

00:19:09.735 --> 00:19:11.535
at the other end,
of course no one is saying

00:19:11.535 --> 00:19:13.311
that,
but we have assumed the mass

00:19:13.311 --> 00:19:15.576
per unit length,
namely M or is this a

00:19:15.576 --> 00:19:17.925
fixed number,
M/L, and then this is

00:19:17.925 --> 00:19:21.527
the answer.
But there are other ways to get

00:19:21.527 --> 00:19:25.900
this result without doing all
the work, okay?

00:19:25.900 --> 00:19:29.604
So, we would like to learn that
other method because it'll save

00:19:29.604 --> 00:19:32.455
you a lot of time.
It must be clear to most people

00:19:32.455 --> 00:19:35.340
that the center of mass of this
rod is at the center.

00:19:35.340 --> 00:19:38.769
But how do we argue that?
How do you make it official?

00:19:38.769 --> 00:19:40.713
If you do the integral you will
get the answer,

00:19:40.713 --> 00:19:42.530
but I want to short circuit the
integral.

00:19:42.530 --> 00:19:45.555
And here is a trick.
It's not going to work for

00:19:45.555 --> 00:19:48.029
arbitrary bodies.
If I give you some crazy object

00:19:48.029 --> 00:19:49.880
like this, you cannot do
anything.

00:19:49.880 --> 00:19:51.750
But this is a very symmetric
object;

00:19:51.750 --> 00:19:54.329
you can sort of tell if I take
the midpoint.

00:19:54.329 --> 00:19:57.519
There is as much stuff to the
right as to the left and somehow

00:19:57.519 --> 00:20:00.238
you want to make that argument
formal, and you do the

00:20:00.238 --> 00:20:02.759
following.
Suppose I have a bunch of

00:20:02.759 --> 00:20:06.196
masses, and the object's really
not even regular,

00:20:06.196 --> 00:20:09.059
and this is my origin of
coordinates.

00:20:09.059 --> 00:20:13.083
If I replace every x by
-x, okay--sorry,

00:20:13.083 --> 00:20:17.790
I should change this object,
so this really looks like this.

00:20:17.790 --> 00:20:21.029
Here's the object.
Suppose I replace every

00:20:21.029 --> 00:20:25.620
x by -x that's
reflecting the body around this

00:20:25.620 --> 00:20:30.256
axis, it will look like this;
it'll be jutting to the right

00:20:30.256 --> 00:20:33.560
instead of the left.
So, don't go by my diagrams.

00:20:33.560 --> 00:20:36.090
You know what I'm trying to do.
I'm trying to draw the mirror

00:20:36.090 --> 00:20:37.680
image of this object the other
way.

00:20:37.680 --> 00:20:40.899
Then, I think it's clear to
everybody, if I do that,

00:20:40.899 --> 00:20:43.964
X will go to -X,
because in this averaging

00:20:43.964 --> 00:20:45.385
m_ix
_i,

00:20:45.385 --> 00:20:47.870
sum of all the masses,
if every x goes to

00:20:47.870 --> 00:20:50.809
-x the center of mass
will go to -X.

00:20:50.809 --> 00:20:55.218
But now, take this rod and
transport every particle to its

00:20:55.218 --> 00:20:58.529
negative coordinate.
And you take that guy and put

00:20:58.529 --> 00:21:02.192
it here, the rod looks the same.
If the rod looks the same,

00:21:02.192 --> 00:21:04.940
the center of mass must look
the same.

00:21:04.940 --> 00:21:09.011
That means -xX has to be
equal to x itself and the

00:21:09.011 --> 00:21:13.175
only answer is X = 0.
So, without doing any detailed

00:21:13.175 --> 00:21:17.329
calculation, you argue that the
answer is X = 0.

00:21:17.329 --> 00:21:19.921
To do this, of course,
you must cleverly pick your

00:21:19.921 --> 00:21:22.990
coordinates so that the symmetry
of the body is evident.

00:21:22.990 --> 00:21:26.652
If you took the body like this
and you took a reflection around

00:21:26.652 --> 00:21:29.309
this point, it goes into body
flipped over.

00:21:29.309 --> 00:21:31.230
There is not much you can say
about it.

00:21:31.230 --> 00:21:34.828
So, what you really want to do
is to pick a point of reflection

00:21:34.828 --> 00:21:37.730
so that upon reflection the body
looks the same;

00:21:37.730 --> 00:21:40.549
the body looks the same,
the answer must be the same.

00:21:40.549 --> 00:21:43.442
But if you argue the answer
must be minus of itself,

00:21:43.442 --> 00:21:46.872
therefore the answer is 0.
This is how the center of mass

00:21:46.872 --> 00:21:48.960
of symmetric bodies can be
found.

00:21:48.960 --> 00:21:51.769
So, we know the answer for this
rod.

00:21:51.769 --> 00:21:58.180
Suppose I give you not a thin
rod, but a rod of non-0 width.

00:21:58.180 --> 00:21:59.799
We want to know its center of
mass;

00:21:59.799 --> 00:22:01.839
we're not going to do any more
work now.

00:22:01.839 --> 00:22:05.397
By symmetry,
I can argue that this has to be

00:22:05.397 --> 00:22:09.451
the center of mass,
because I can take every point

00:22:09.451 --> 00:22:14.416
here and turn it into the point
there by changing y to

00:22:14.416 --> 00:22:17.231
-y;
therefore, capital Y

00:22:17.231 --> 00:22:20.378
will become minus capital
Y, but the body looks the

00:22:20.378 --> 00:22:22.890
same after this mapping.
So, capital Y is 0,

00:22:22.890 --> 00:22:25.245
and similarly capital X
is 0, and that's the center of

00:22:25.245 --> 00:22:25.560
mass.

00:22:30.259 --> 00:22:38.494
Okay, now, what if I give you
this object, anybody want to try

00:22:38.494 --> 00:22:39.440
that?

00:22:44.500 --> 00:22:49.996
Would you guys like to try this?
Yes, can you tell me where the

00:22:49.996 --> 00:22:53.940
center of mass should be,
yeah?

00:22:53.940 --> 00:22:55.640
No, no, the guy in front of
you, yes.

00:22:55.640 --> 00:22:59.111
Student: The center of
mass, you can't get the center

00:22:59.111 --> 00:23:05.794
of mass with two objects,
and then this is where you said

00:23:05.794 --> 00:23:13.519
over in the curve,
find the center between those

00:23:13.519 --> 00:23:16.492
two masses.
Professor Ramamurti

00:23:16.492 --> 00:23:17.990
Shankar: Okay,
is that what your answer was?

00:23:17.990 --> 00:23:22.135
Okay, so the correct answer is,
replace this mass by all of its

00:23:22.135 --> 00:23:24.609
mass, whatever it is,
sitting here.

00:23:24.609 --> 00:23:26.930
Replace this one by all of its
mass sitting here;

00:23:26.930 --> 00:23:30.740
then, forget the big bodies,
replace them by points.

00:23:30.740 --> 00:23:32.737
Then, he's got two masses
located here,

00:23:32.737 --> 00:23:34.840
and you can find the weighted
average.

00:23:34.840 --> 00:23:36.060
It may be somewhere there.

00:23:41.569 --> 00:23:45.779
Okay, now let's take one more
object.

00:23:45.779 --> 00:23:49.289
Then I'm pretty much done with
finding these centers of mass.

00:23:49.289 --> 00:23:54.089
The object I'm going to pick is
a triangle that looks like this;

00:23:54.089 --> 00:23:58.244
it's supposed to be symmetric,
even though I've drawn it this

00:23:58.244 --> 00:24:00.238
way.
That is b and that is

00:24:00.238 --> 00:24:02.550
b, and that distance is
h;

00:24:02.550 --> 00:24:08.598
let the mass be M.
Where is the center of mass of

00:24:08.598 --> 00:24:11.352
this object?
Again, by symmetry,

00:24:11.352 --> 00:24:16.025
you can tell that the y
coordinate of the center of mass

00:24:16.025 --> 00:24:20.258
must lie on this line,
because if I take y to

00:24:20.258 --> 00:24:24.549
-y, it maps onto itself
so it looks the same.

00:24:24.549 --> 00:24:26.619
But it's supposed to reverse
capital Y;

00:24:26.619 --> 00:24:29.180
therefore, Y is
-Y and therefore it's 0;

00:24:29.180 --> 00:24:33.329
so, it's evidently lying
somewhere on this line.

00:24:33.329 --> 00:24:36.225
I cannot do further
calculations of this type by

00:24:36.225 --> 00:24:39.737
saying where it is on the line,
because it has no longer a

00:24:39.737 --> 00:24:42.140
symmetry in the x
direction;

00:24:42.140 --> 00:24:45.250
it's symmetric on the y
after flipping y,

00:24:45.250 --> 00:24:47.670
but I cannot take x to
-x.

00:24:47.670 --> 00:24:51.580
In fact, if I take x to
-x this one looks like

00:24:51.580 --> 00:24:53.900
this, it doesn't map into
itself.

00:24:53.900 --> 00:24:56.526
But I can pick any point here;
if I take x to

00:24:56.526 --> 00:24:58.339
-x, the object looks
different.

00:24:58.339 --> 00:25:01.638
It looks like that object and
relating one object to another

00:25:01.638 --> 00:25:05.105
object is what I'm trying to do.
I want to relate it to the same

00:25:05.105 --> 00:25:06.729
object.
That cannot be done for

00:25:06.729 --> 00:25:08.390
x.
It can be done for y;

00:25:08.390 --> 00:25:10.890
for x you've got to do
some honest work.

00:25:10.890 --> 00:25:16.008
The honest work we will do then
is to take this thing,

00:25:16.008 --> 00:25:20.258
take a strip here,
with location x and

00:25:20.258 --> 00:25:24.527
width dx,
and the height of that strip

00:25:24.527 --> 00:25:28.272
here is y;
y of course varies with

00:25:28.272 --> 00:25:30.889
x.
So, I'm going to argue that to

00:25:30.889 --> 00:25:34.629
find the center of mass of this
triangle I can divide it into

00:25:34.629 --> 00:25:37.869
vertical strips which are
parallel to each other,

00:25:37.869 --> 00:25:41.766
and find the center of mass by
adding the weighted average of

00:25:41.766 --> 00:25:44.755
all these things.
For that, I need to know what's

00:25:44.755 --> 00:25:50.390
the mass of the shaded region.
So, let's call it δm.

00:25:50.390 --> 00:25:54.500
The mass of the shaded region
is the mass per unit area.

00:25:54.500 --> 00:25:57.413
I'll find the area later on in
terms of b and h,

00:25:57.413 --> 00:26:01.316
but this is mass per unit area.
Then, I need to know the area

00:26:01.316 --> 00:26:04.107
of the strip.
I'm going to give the answer

00:26:04.107 --> 00:26:06.430
because I don't have time to
probe it.

00:26:06.430 --> 00:26:10.036
But you should think about what
the answer for the area of the

00:26:10.036 --> 00:26:13.160
shaded region is.
It's got a height 2y,

00:26:13.160 --> 00:26:15.589
and it's got the width
dx.

00:26:15.589 --> 00:26:18.364
It's not quite a rectangle
because the edges are slightly

00:26:18.364 --> 00:26:21.189
tapered, but when δx
goes to 0, it's going to look

00:26:21.189 --> 00:26:26.369
like a rectangle.
So, the area is 2yδx.

00:26:26.369 --> 00:26:29.890
But I don't want to write
everything in terms of y.

00:26:29.890 --> 00:26:31.740
I want to write it in terms of
x;

00:26:31.740 --> 00:26:37.636
then, I do similar triangles.
Similar triangles tell me that

00:26:37.636 --> 00:26:43.405
y/b is x/h,
namely, that triangle compared

00:26:43.405 --> 00:26:49.069
to that triangle tells me
y/b is x/h.

00:26:49.069 --> 00:26:54.900
Therefore, the y here
can be replaced by bx/h.

00:27:02.349 --> 00:27:06.424
So, that is the mass of the
sliver here, and its center is

00:27:06.424 --> 00:27:09.212
obviously here,
so that is a mass there,

00:27:09.212 --> 00:27:12.090
there's a mass there;
I've got to do the weighted

00:27:12.090 --> 00:27:13.625
average of all of them.
So remember,

00:27:13.625 --> 00:27:15.650
I don't just integrate this
over x;

00:27:15.650 --> 00:27:17.359
that would just give me the
mass of the body.

00:27:17.359 --> 00:27:21.567
I should multiply it by a
further x and then do the

00:27:21.567 --> 00:27:24.483
integral.
So, what I really want to do to

00:27:24.483 --> 00:27:28.215
find the center of mass
x, is to take that mass I

00:27:28.215 --> 00:27:31.184
got,
M/A, there is a 2,

00:27:31.184 --> 00:27:35.176
there's an h,
there is a b,

00:27:35.176 --> 00:27:38.670
there is an x from
there,

00:27:38.670 --> 00:27:41.554
and another x,
because you have to multiply

00:27:41.554 --> 00:27:44.380
this by the x coordinate
of this thing,

00:27:44.380 --> 00:27:46.920
because that's the coordinate
of the center of mass of this.

00:27:46.920 --> 00:27:49.966
There are two xs,
that's what you've got to

00:27:49.966 --> 00:27:53.012
remember.
So, that should be integrated

00:27:53.012 --> 00:27:57.250
from 0 to h,
that'll give me h^(3)/3.

00:27:57.250 --> 00:28:04.450
So, I get (2Mb/Ah) times
h^(3) over 3.

00:28:09.269 --> 00:28:11.259
Now, you know there is one more
thing we have to do.

00:28:11.259 --> 00:28:15.669
We must replace the area of the
